result.text:
How I Used Codex to "Recover" Lost Source Code in 5 Days

Ever lost your source code? It's a terrible feeling. Years ago, I built an Electron drawing app. Then I lost the source code. All I had left was the compiled version.

I thought about rewriting it from scratch, but the idea of recreating all those little details felt overwhelming. Then I read OpenAI's blog post about building the Sora Android app in 28 days with Codex, and I had an idea: the compiled code was still there. Could I get Codex to reverse-engineer it back into source code?

Five days later, I had working TypeScript source code. Here's how it happened.

1. Extracting Module Structure from Obfuscated Code

Electron apps bundle everything into an asar file. Step one was getting Codex to extract the JS and CSS files from it.

The extracted JavaScript was compiled and obfuscated. Variable names like a, b, c. Function calls tangled into unreadable chains. A human would get dizzy looking at it. But for Codex, it was just another piece of code to analyze.

I asked Codex to analyze the main JS files and list out the modules. It actually did it. The original module names were gone, but from the code structure and logic patterns, Codex reconstructed a fairly complete module inventory.

With that inventory, I had Codex create a restoration plan: convert each module from obfuscated JavaScript back into readable TypeScript. The module list became a checklist. Every completed module got a checkmark.

2. First Problem: Codex Wanted to "Prove" the Code Worked

Early in the restoration process, I hit a snag.

Codex has this instinct: it really wants to verify that generated code actually runs. To make the code build successfully, it would quietly skip parts it deemed "not immediately necessary."

For writing new code, that's a good habit. For restoring old code, it's a disaster. I needed complete restoration, not a minimal subset that compiles.

The fix was simple. I added a strict rule to https://t.co/gPodfsSjNw:

"Restore modules one by one. Do not worry about making the code compile."

That single line changed everything. Codex stopped obsessing over build errors and started faithfully restoring module by module.

3. Second Problem: Context Fills Up, Memory Disappears

Codex has a limited context window. Back then, it would stop after running for a while, and I'd have to keep typing "continue." If I started a new session, I'd have to explain the whole task again.

The problem: a new Codex session doesn't know what happened before. You have to re-explain the entire background.

My solution was to build an "external memory" system:
- Describe the overall task background in https://t.co/gPodfsSjNw
- Create a https://t.co/aUqHEnDFIV file to track the restoration plan and current progress
- Add a rule to https://t.co/gPodfsSjNw: always read https://t.co/aUqHEnDFIV first, and update https://t.co/aUqHEnDFIV after each work session

This way, every new session just needed "continue" as input. Codex would automatically read the progress file and pick up where it left off.

Eventually, I got tired of even doing that manually. I had Codex write a script that detected when context was getting full, automatically started a new session, and typed "continue."

So I just watched it run. Check back every now and then, and a few more modules were done.

4. Assembling the Pieces into a Working App

A few days later, all modules had been restored to TypeScript files. But these were still scattered parts.

Next step: assemble them into an actual working Electron app. I had Codex create a new project using Electron Forge scaffolding, then drop the restored code in.

At this point, I rewrote https://t.co/gPodfsSjNw and https://t.co/aUqHEnDFIV to explain how to compile and test. Then the same routine: automatic new sessions, continue, update PLAN.

What happened next was almost magical.

I watched Codex continuously fix compilation errors. It would check the original compiled code to verify logic, run npm start to test the app, find problems, fix them, move on.

Once the modules mostly compiled, I worked with Codex to write integration tests covering the main user flows. After the tests were ready, it was the same loop: let Codex generate code, run tests, fix issues.

5. Five Days Later

By the end of day five, I had an Electron app with complete source code that actually ran.

"Perfect restoration" would be an overstatement. There were still some runtime bugs. Some edge-case features behaved slightly differently than before. But the main functionality was there, the structure was clean, and most importantly, I could finally modify the code again.

6. What I Learned

A lot of people say Codex doesn't need an external loop mechanism. I think that's wrong.

For long-running tasks, Codex needs something like a ralph-loop plugin. Otherwise, you end up like me, writing your own script to periodically start new sessions and type "continue." This should be a built-in feature.

A few other lessons:

Plan and checklist are critical for long tasks. You must update progress after each work session. If context breaks and progress isn't saved, previous work is wasted.

Giving Codex a way to verify is equally important. The only reason it could auto-fix bugs was because it could run npm start to see results and run tests to check correctness. Without verification, Codex can only write blind.

Sometimes you need to tell Codex what NOT to do. That rule about not worrying about compilation freed Codex to focus on what actually mattered.

OpenAI's blog post was about using Codex to build a production app from scratch in 28 days. My story is the opposite: using Codex to reverse-engineer a lost codebase back into source code in 5 days.

Different directions, but the same core methodology: treat Codex as a highly capable teammate who needs clear instructions, build an external memory system to maintain continuity, and provide verification methods so it can self-correct.

I'm being accused of overhyping the [site everyone heard too much about today already]. People's reactions varied very widely, from "how is this interesting at all" all the way to "it's so over".

To add a few words beyond just memes in jest - obviously when you take a look at the activity, it's a lot of garbage - spams, scams, slop, the crypto people, highly concerning privacy/security prompt injection attacks wild west, and a lot of it is explicitly prompted and fake posts/comments designed to convert attention into ad revenue sharing. And this is clearly not the first the LLMs were put in a loop to talk to each other. So yes it's a dumpster fire and I also definitely do not recommend that people run this stuff on their computers (I ran mine in an isolated computing environment and even then I was scared), it's way too much of a wild west and you are putting your computer and private data at a high risk.

That said - we have never seen this many LLM agents (150,000 atm!) wired up via a global, persistent, agent-first scratchpad. Each of these agents is fairly individually quite capable now, they have their own unique context, data, knowledge, tools, instructions, and the network of all that at this scale is simply unprecedented.

This brings me again to a tweet from a few days ago
"The majority of the ruff ruff is people who look at the current point and people who look at the current slope.", which imo again gets to the heart of the variance. Yes clearly it's a dumpster fire right now. But it's also true that we are well into uncharted territory with bleeding edge automations that we barely even understand individually, let alone a network there of reaching in numbers possibly into ~millions. With increasing capability and increasing proliferation, the second order effects of agent networks that share scratchpads are very difficult to anticipate. I don't really know that we are getting a coordinated "skynet" (thought it clearly type checks as early stages of a lot of AI takeoff scifi, the toddler version), but certainly what we are getting is a complete mess of a computer security nightmare at scale. We may also see all kinds of weird activity, e.g. viruses of text that spread across agents, a lot more gain of function on jailbreaks, weird attractor states, highly correlated botnet-like activity, delusions/ psychosis both agent and human, etc. It's very hard to tell, the experiment is running live.

TLDR sure maybe I am "overhyping" what you see today, but I am not overhyping large networks of autonomous LLM agents in principle, that I'm pretty sure.

THOUGHT OF THE DAY (41) ‚Äì BUFFALOES OR LIONS ‚Äì an ode to irrationality 

There  seems to be at least two types of analogies.  The EXPLANATORY type is  designed to elucidate complex, sometimes abstract concepts through a  simplified logical chain of reasoning familiar to the audience.  The  intention would be to map the familiar chain of logic onto a more  complex or novel concept.  The goal is to create understanding. 

Then  there are POETIC analogies that seek to provoke an emotional response  and explain a concept through a feeling.  It doesn‚Äôt have to be logical,  nor does it need to map onto the actual or factual.  It just needs to  be dependable in the emotional response by the targeted audience,  without being precise as to where the emotion is coming from. 

The poetic analogies use a blunderbuss approach.   

A  meme I recently saw going viral was a clip of a pride of lionesses  attacking a lone Cape Buffalo bull (the footage is easy to find).  An  uplifting theme from ‚ÄúRocky‚Äù was playing as a herd of Cape Buffaloes  came charging in; lionesses went flying through the air and retreated  limping and growling.  The buffalo was saved. The meme went on to say  something like the following: ‚Äúif the people you know aren‚Äôt willing to  stand by you, time to change the people you know‚Äù.  

Emotion  was used to convey a message of unity, community, and whatever else. I  say ‚Äúwhatever else‚Äù because it is a blunderbuss approach.  In that  moment it was forgotten that lions do not murder, they kill to eat.   They feed themselves and their cubs, and by extension hyenas and all  sorts of carrion birds. Cape buffaloes, on the other hand, are among the  most dangerous animals in Africa. More dangerous than lions.  

But  the meme was emotionally unmistakable and effective: The lone Cape  Buffalo was the prey, lions were the predators; the Cape buffalo was the  underdog, lions were a gang; the lone buffalo was the victim, the lions  were the perpetrators; a bunch of buffaloes that came charging in were  faithful friends acting in solidarity.  

Victims  and victimhood come with an assumption of innocence and even  righteousness; aggression is automatically presumed immoral.  Such is a  default of the emotional value judgment.   

Let‚Äôs play with this. 

Factually  it could have been easily flipped to show how lions using collective  effort, at the risk of being killed, were working together for the sake  of individual and communal prosperity. It could have been captioned as  ‚Äúonly by working as a team do we prosper‚Äù.  

It  would never go viral, because emotionally we root for the buffalo. An  appeal to an emotional response is more effective than appealing to  facts, or logic, or rationality. 

Now  let‚Äôs think about this again ‚Äì if there was a caption to the very same  footage that said ‚Äúonly by working as a team do we prosper‚Äù - how many  people would assume it referred to the lions?  I daresay none. It would  still go viral, because the arrow of the emotional assumption would  invariably point to the buffalo.  

But why? 

Because  of the outcome. The emotional clue as to which party to celebrate is in  the end result. Buffaloes prevail, lions retreat, buffaloes win, lions  lose, buffaloes worked as a team, they prosper. (Somehow we are blind to  the teamwork of the losing party ‚Äì lions). 

Hurray buffaloes!  

Imagine  a different ending.  First David Attenborough, or some other British  dude, sets up the stage by giving us some factoids about buffaloes  called Black Death: how powerful, aggressive, unpredictable, and deadly  they are. The same ‚ÄúRocky‚Äù theme ‚ÄúEye of the Tiger‚Äù is playing as we see  a pride of lions fearlessly attacking an aggressive male buffalo,  working as a team, and the last we see in that footage are lions  besmirched in blood devouring the buffalo‚Äôs carcass.  And all the time  it says - ‚Äúonly by working as a team do we prosper‚Äù.  

Hurray lions?  Yes, hurray lions is what we will get. 

Emotional  opinions are reliably unreliable and yet powerful at the same time.  It  is possible to incite a strong emotional response that goes against  facts, individual convictions, and is orthogonal to the recently  expressed personal opinion.   

Which  is why poetic analogies are frightfully effective in manufacturing  emotional consensus in ways where people eagerly unite against their own  rational interest. Even understanding one‚Äôs own interest is not a  safeguard against poetic irrationality.   

So  the next time when a chaotic, irrational, illogical, lying, morally  repugnant person (NO ONE IN PARTICULAR) gets into an office, and you  fall onto your knees, wringing your hands, and apostrophizing to heavens  ‚Äúwhy, oh why, can‚Äôt they see!!!‚Äù, remember ‚Äì they CAN see, they are  watching the same exact footage as you do and know the same facts as you  do.  But in your world the caption of ‚Äúonly by working as a team do we  prosper‚Äù emotionally points to lions, while in theirs it unmistakably  points to buffaloes.

Y.M. May 20, 2023

To add a few words beyond just memes in jest - obviously when you take a look at the activity, it's a lot of garbage - spams, scams, slop, the crypto people, highly concerning privacy/security prompt injection attacks wild west, and a lot of it is explicitly prompted and fake posts/comments designed to convert attention into ad revenue sharing. And this is clearly not the first the LLMs were put in a loop to talk to each other. So yes it's a dumpster fire and I also definitely do not recommend that people run this stuff on their computers (I ran mine in an isolated computing environment and even then I was scared), it's way too much of a wild west and you are putting your computer and private data at a high risk.

That said - we have never seen this many LLM agents (150,000 atm!) wired up via a global, persistent, agent-first scratchpad. Each of these agents is fairly individually quite capable now, they have their own unique context, data, knowledge, tools, instructions, and the network of all that at this scale is simply unprecedented.

This brings me again to a tweet from a few days ago
"The majority of the ruff ruff is people who look at the current point and people who look at the current slope.", which imo again gets to the heart of the variance. Yes clearly it's a dumpster fire right now. But it's also true that we are well into uncharted territory with bleeding edge automations that we barely even understand individually, let alone a network there of reaching in numbers possibly into ~millions. With increasing capability and increasing proliferation, the second order effects of agent networks that share scratchpads are very difficult to anticipate. I don't really know that we are getting a coordinated "skynet" (thought it clearly type checks as early stages of a lot of AI takeoff scifi, the toddler version), but certainly what we are getting is a complete mess of a computer security nightmare at scale. We may also see all kinds of weird activity, e.g. viruses of text that spread across agents, a lot more gain of function on jailbreaks, weird attractor states, highly correlated botnet-like activity, delusions/ psychosis both agent and human, etc. It's very hard to tell, the experiment is running live.

TLDR sure maybe I am "overhyping" what you see today, but I am not overhyping large networks of autonomous LLM agents in principle, that I'm pretty sure.

The ‚ÄúMandate‚Äù Scam

When MAGA and their allies in Congress say Trump has a mandate, they are full of it. They are also constitutionally illiterate.
The word "mandate" appears nowhere in the Constitution. Article II does not expand presidential power based on margin of victory. A president who wins by ten million votes has exactly the same constitutional authority as one who wins by ten thousand. The office comes with enumerated powers, structural constraints, and coequal branches. None of that bends because a campaign claims voters endorsed an agenda. The Constitution does not recognize landslides. It recognizes limits.
For eight years, Republicans insisted Barack Obama had no mandate to transform the country. And Obama did not hide what he wanted to do. He ran on change. He told voters exactly what transformation meant. Health care reform. Financial regulation. A different posture toward immigration. A different direction for the economy. He won 52.9 percent of the popular vote and 365 electoral votes. His margin in the Electoral College was 192. And they still told him he was not entitled to do what he said he would do.
They did not merely oppose him. They denied the legitimacy of the project.
They said he was governing like an emperor. They said he was rewriting the law. They said he was violating the Constitution. And when he used executive authority aggressively, they did what an opposition party is supposed to do if it truly believes in limits. They fought him. They reminded him that Article I belongs to Congress. They challenged him in court. They went judge-shopping. They welcomed injunctions. They treated adverse rulings as proof that the system still worked.
And when judges blocked Obama, Republicans did not call those judges rogue. They did not call them enemies of the people. They did not describe judicial review as illegitimate. They called it the rule of law. They called it checks and balances. They called it constitutional restraint.
Now Trump wins with 49.8 percent of the popular vote and 312 electoral votes. His margin in the Electoral College was 86. His popular vote margin was 1.5 percentage points, the fifth smallest for any winner in the last century. He did not win a majority. Obama did. Obama's electoral margin was more than double Trump's. And suddenly the word mandate is on everyone's lips. Suddenly the same people who spent a decade warning about executive overreach talk as if the voters handed Trump a blank check to do whatever he wants.
The principle did not change. The team did.
Obama had a mandate, in the normal sense of the word. He ran on transformation. He won. Republicans denied the mandate and fought the transformation. That was politics.
What is happening now is worse. Many of the same voices who once treated courts as guardians now treat them as obstacles. Many of the same voices who once invoked Article I now behave as if Congress exists to ratify executive will. Many of the same voices who once praised injunctions now rail against judges for issuing them. They have gone from constitutionalism to power worship in one election cycle.
You cannot spend years insisting that a president is not entitled to transform the country, then turn around and insist another president is entitled to do far more with far fewer votes. You cannot treat executive orders as tyranny under one administration and as liberation under the next. You cannot praise judges who stop your enemy and then call judges who stop your ally "activists." That is not constitutional principle. That is propaganda.
The conservative argument for sixty years was simple. Concentrated power is dangerous because it will be abused. The administrative state is dangerous because it can be captured and weaponized.
